We use a dynamic programming approach to mark numbers that can be formed. Starting from 0, we check each number up to 50 (as a reasonable upper bound) to see if it can be formed by any combination of 6, 10, and 15. After checking each number, we find the following numbers that cannot be formed: 11, 17, 19, 23, 29. Checking further, we confirm that all numbers greater than 29 can be formed using combinations of 6, 10, and 15.
